      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Holmium is a silvery-coloured, soft and malleable metal. It can be rolled into very thin sheets. Holmium is a member of the lanthanide series. On contact with air it becomes covered with a layer of holmium oxide -  H</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">o</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. Holmium reacts with water to produce holmium hydroxide, </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Ho(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">In the reaction with acids holmium forms salts. It was discovered in 1878 by the Swiss chemists </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Louis Soret and Marc Delafontaine and, independently, by the Swedish chemist Per Theodor Cleve. It was named after </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Stockholm (Holmia in Latin).</text>
